        }
      ]
    },
    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "children": [
        {
          "text": "Religion was foundational to life in ancient Egypt, particularly in relation to the afterlife. The god Mehen, often depicted as a coiled snake, played a significant role in these beliefs due to his close association to the sun god Ra and the journey to the afterlife."
        }
      ]
    },
    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "children": [
        {
          "text": ""
        }
      ]
    },
    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "children": [
        {
          "text": "The board of this game, named by contemporary scholars after the diety, resembles a coiled snake. "
        },
        {
          "text": "Mehen ",
          "italic": true
        },
        {
          "text": "is thought to be a board game played by ancient Egyptians during the First to Sixth Dynasties. Various types of "
        },
        {
          "text": "Mehen ",
          "italic": true
        },
        {
          "text": "boards have been found throughout different tombs, suggesting that it was a popular game, and that it was directly linked to beliefs around helping the tomb's owner transition to the afterlife."
        }
      ]
    },
    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "children": [
        {
          "text": "\n"
        }
      ]
    },
    {
      "uuid": "a3ea86aa-a0d5-4c31-9534-0b11e81bbeab",
      "includes": [
        "media",
